Nine conditions rooted in wise consideration When a monk practises wise consideration joy arises in him and from his being joyful delight arises and from his feeling delight his senses are calmed as a result of this calming he feels happiness and from his feeling happy his mind becomes concentrated with his mind thus concentrated he knows and sees things as they really are with his thus knowing and seeing things as they really are he becomes disenchanted with disenchantment he becomes dispassionate and by dispassion he is liberated
